Comparing images shot on the @canonusa 5D Mark IV to ones from my new Canon R5 gifted from @bhphoto & @bh.creators 📸 

For each of these shots, I used the same camera settings (ISO, shutter speed, aperture, and Kelvin white balance) as well as the same lens (Canon EF35mm F1.4 - I used an adapter with the R5). 

Both are incredible cameras. So here’s my first impressions when it comes to image quality …

- The R5 quality is WAY sharper (45MP sensor vs. 30MP on the Mark IV)
- The R5 performs better in low light
- The R5 has amazing face and eye tracking which makes autofocusing faster and easier. For me, this is the most exciting difference; I’m blown away by how quickly it tracks the eye even when using an EF-mount lens with an adapter!!
- The RAW images on the R5 seem cooler and slightly more desaturated in color in these images, whereas the RAW images on the Mark IV seem warmer and more saturated

My overall takeaway?

Although the colors are slightly different than what I’m used to, you can play around with changing the Color Profiles in Lightroom from “Adobe RAW” to “Camera Matching” profiles, which bring back the saturation. 

There are soooo many exciting aspects to the Canon R5 that I’m beyond stoked about the upgrade! I’ll be sharing more of my favorite features soon 💓📸

Link to camera:

https://www.bhphotovideo.com/c/product/1547009-REG/canon_eos_r5_mirrorless_digital.html

Had so much fun creating with @nefan_ and @savanahnormanmua the other day 💓 Speaking of creating … 

I watched a recent interview with (my queen) Taylor Swift and I wanted to share what she said about her creative process that I really loved:

“I’m making more albums at a more rapid pace than I ever did before. I think the more art you create, hopefully the less pressure you put on yourself. If you stay ready, you don’t have to get ready. If you keep making stuff, you just keep making stuff and hopefully you get better at it. You don’t have to belabor it, or polish the doorknob so long that you forget to open the door.”

I think as creatives we all suffer from impostor syndrome in one way or another, and social media is a double edged sword that can inspire us but also make us feel insecure. 

What Taylor said about creating more often is something I really think is so important an can be applied to any niche including photography - I think sometimes with the amount of information and education and tutorials out there, we can get caught up in consuming and learning all the things but never actually put it into practice. 

The best way to grow your skills and perfect your craft is through practice - even if it’s not perfect or the best, the more often you’re shooting and experimenting, the quicker you’ll see that your art will improve. Try not to worry so much about what other people will think of it and just START. 

Anyways, rambling over - I just thought this topic was important and wanted to share my thoughts with you 🫶🏻

Thanks to @bhphoto & @bh.creators, I switched from the @canonusa 5D Mark IV to the Canon R5 and I haven’t regretted it one second 🤩 

Here’s three reasons you should think about switching over to a mirrorless camera like the R5 … 

1. Electronic viewfinder 📸 Being able to see how your images will actually look through the electronic viewfinder is such an amazing feature of using a mirrorless camera. I no longer have to take test shots to see if my image is exposed properly - I can see it all in real time!

2. Super quick eye and head detection 👀 I’m blownnn away at how accurate the R5 can track my subject’s eyes and head even while moving around quickly. This is a huge game changer - I can worry less about nailing the focus at low apertures and focus on the creative side of shooting. 

3. Insanely sharp images 🌆 The Canon R5 has a 45MP sensor which means my images are so much sharper, so I can zoom in on my files super close and still see every little detail. 

As much as I love my DSLR that served me for years and still does an amazing job, switching to mirrorless has overall made my technical process of shooting so much easier so I can focus on the creative part, which is my fave part anyways <3 

Check out the selection of @canonusa mirrorless cameras from @bhphoto via the link below:

Here’s 3 things I did when I first started my photo business in Utah that directly lead to paid work:

1. ATTENDING STYLED SHOOTS - after moving from Florida to Utah, I didn’t have any photos in my portfolio that looked like I was even based here. I started attending styled photo shoots to expand my portfolio and start shooting in popular locations near me. Whether you create a styled shoot yourself or attend someone else’s, any event where you can build a diverse portfolio filled with images you’d love to shoot with a paying client will help you do so. I was able to show people what type of work they could expect if they booked with me. Always show, not tell! (Now I host styled shoot events - check out @shotatcolorpop !)

2. START AN AFFILIATE PROGRAM - When I got my first ever paying client after relocating (senior portrait session), I let them know that if they referred any of their friends to me for their own photos, I would pay them a commission. This was something I had never tried before but it actually worked! If you’re struggling to book new clients but have an archive of past ones, reach out to them and let them know you have an affiliate program. Word of mouth is still a great way to get booked. 

3. PITCH TO LOCAL BRANDS - Directly pitching myself to local brands is another way I was able to get hired. Create a PDF file with your best work ( but make sure it’s similar in style to the brand you’re emailing) and let them know you’d love to be considered for any upcoming projects. Make sure to keep it brief and include direct links to your portfolio! 

Let me know if you’ve tried these methods and found success!

No studio, no problem 📸

I can’t believe these photos are almost 3 years old!! Before we bought our house last year and I was able to turn the shed into a studio, I did so many shoots on the kitchen floor of my apartment.

Most of the time I used natural light coming in through my one window, but occasionally I used strobes or continuous lights. 

I had a really cheap backdrop stand from Amazon and used only bedsheets for a while until I started buying seamless paper rolls. It was really fun to see how creative we could get with props and lighting just from around the house.

It was such a pain to set everything up and take it down after a shoot, so I’m happy to have a designed studio space now - but this was definitely an era I love looking back on. 💓

Literally makes my heart burst when someone draws or paints one of my photos. I still have a bunch of prints in my office! 💓 I love seeing the way everyone reimagines the photos and adds their own creative touches. Shoutout to these incredible artists:

Here’s 3 ways you can get more variety during a photo shoot:

1. Switch up your angle 📸 First, try getting down low and shoot upwards at your subject. A lot of the time I end up laying down on my back on the ground or using a wide angle lens for creative shots. I also love to bring a step stool to my shoots so I can shoot downwards at my subject for a birds eye view. 

2. Outfit or prop change 📸 Sometimes just switching out an outfit or a prop can bring a whole new look to your shoot. Bring a few options with you and it’ll make the set of images feel so different! 

3. Shoot from different distances 📸 During your shoot, make sure to get images from farther away as well as closer up detail shots. Remember you can always crop in but you can’t crop out! Using lenses with different focal lengths helps with this as well.

Anything can be a backdrop if you just ✨believe✨

Here are some of my favorite materials to use as backdrops to bring more visual interest to my images! When choosing a backdrop, keep in mind the texture, movement, and color of the material and how it can help tell your story. 

Here’s where you can find these materials:

1. Plastic (you can get plastic drop cloth at Home Depot for less than $3, or use a shower curtain liner)

2. Mylar (search Mylar roll on Amazon)

3. Canvas (check out @ultravioletbackdrops )

4. Curtains (like for your windows!)

5. Paper seamless rolls (you can get them from @savageuniversal )

6. Cellophane (super cheap at the craft store, we’ve also used iridescent shower curtains)

7. Vinyl (this one I used was from Amazon for a kids birthday party lol, you can also use tablecloths!)

8. Tinsel (from the party store!)

You guys really liked the last camera settings video I posted so here’s another, this time with settings for some of my favorite shots that included quick movements! 

In general I’d recommend a shutter speed of around 1/300 or higher to avoid motion blur - but the settings you choose will always be dependent on the lighting, so these are not an exact recipe! 

When shooting in harsh light, I still like to keep my aperture as low as possible so I tend to raise my shutter speed 📸

Here’s how I use the @canonusa Camera Connect app to take photos of myself remotely!

Step 1: You need a camera with Bluetooth/WiFi compatibility (I’m using the Canon EOS R5)

Step 2: Connect via Bluetooth or Wifi to your mobile device (the first time you connect you’ll need to put in the password which you can find on the camera screen)

Step 3: Open Canon’s app called Camera Connect, wait for the camera to show up, and click Shoot

Step 4: From here you can control the camera by changing the settings, pressing the shutter, and reviewing and importing images straight to your device!

It’s World Photography Day! It’s been a long time since I introduced myself on the feed so I thought todays the day 📸

⭐️I’m Marina, I’m 28 and I’m a creative portrait photographer based in Salt Lake City, UT but I’m from Florida originally!

⭐️I’ve been interested in photography since my first point and shoot as a kid, but I started taking it more seriously in high school. I got my degree in Studio Art with a focus in Photography from Florida State University in 2017!

⭐️I moved to Utah for its gorgeous landscapes and seasons. It’s the perfect place for photography and the creative community here is so big! 

⭐️I started creating educational resources for photographers in 2020. I launched a community called Made to Make where I’ve shared 100+ video lessons!

⭐️In 2021 @artdeptcreative and I started a business called Colorpop, hosting styled shoot workshops where photographers from around the world join us every year to shoot 10+ epic colorful editorial concepts in 1 weekend! @shotatcolorpop 🌈

⭐️When I’m not shooting or working, I’m usually hanging with my husband and our dog, listening to Taylor Swift, playing the Sims, rollerblading, or watching Rupauls Drag Race 🫶🏻

Photography has taken me so many places around the world and introduced me to the most talented and creative people. 

Whether you’ve just followed along or been here for a while, thank you for support and love! Let me know what you want to learn more about 📸

Because of the rising popularity of Generative AI in the photography world, a lot of us have had questions around how we can ensure to be properly credited for our work, and how we’ll be able to tell if something is real or AI generated. 

I’m passionate about partnering with @Adobe to share more about how they’re integrating Content Credentials, which helps creators get recognized for their work, build their following, and provide creative transparency. 

Content Credentials essentially act as a nutrition label for your work - with info on HOW it was created (if AI was used) and WHO created it (name and social links). When you enable Content Credentials in Photoshop, a layer of verifiable information is attached to your work. And when your work is shared on a platform that supports Content Credentials, it provides the viewer context around its creation. 
 
As a photographer that uses Generative AI in their work, I’m really excited about this feature because transparency is KEY!! I can’t wait to see the way this changes how we’re credited for our work and how we share it with the world 📸 #AdobePartner

My 2023 “Life Wrapped” if you will …

At the end of each year I really try to take time to reflect on the wins and lessons so I can learn from them.

I was extra curious this year, so I decided to total up some numbers and make my own version of life “wrapped” if you will haha. 

This year I …

📸 Did 60 photo shoots
👩🏻‍🦰 Did 17 self portrait shoots
📱 Posted 177 Reels and 46 image carousels
✈️ Traveled to 4 countries and 18 states
🎤 Hosted 3 workshops and spoke at 2 events
🕺🏻 Went to 6 weddings and 3 bachelorette parties

And here’s what I learned:

Because I traveled so much this year, I had to learn how to say NO to things in order to prioritize what was most important for my business and mental health, which was definitely a challenge I’m still figuring out.

I started prioritizing posting Reels on Instagram instead of image carousels, which helped me grow over 200,000 followers since January.

I did LESS photo shoots this year than I ever have since going full time with photography, but it taught me so much about quality over quantity and being more intentional with my work.

And because I had less new work to share, I made more of an effort to repurpose old content which (surprisingly to me) paid off. REPOST YOUR OLD STUFF!!!

I didn’t accomplish all the goals I had this year, and that’s okay. It’s all about the journey. I just wanted to share a couple of these lessons I learned with you in case they help with navigating your own path in photography or business - it can be so hard to juggle it all, but you got this! Sending you love 💓
